Operator overloading allows you to define new behaviors for existing operators when used with user-defined data types (classes). For example, you can overload the + operator to add two custom objects.

typescript

Copy code

class MyString {
public:
    MyString operator+(const MyString& other) {
        MyString result = *this;
        result += other;
        return result;
    }
};

The mutable keyword is used to indicate that a member variable of a class can be modified even within a const-qualified member function. It allows for logical constness while enabling changes to specific data members.

typescript

Copy code

int x = 5;
auto lambda = [x]() mutable { x++; };
lambda(); // x is now 6

Function overloading is a feature that allows multiple functions with the same name but different parameter lists to be defined within the same scope. The appropriate function to call is determined based on the number or types of arguments provided.

typescript

Copy code

int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

double add(double a, double b) {
    return a + b;
}

